231
00:12:53,496 --> 00:12:56,418
Particularly at the start of the fight when everyone's still at 100%.

232
00:13:00,678 --> 00:13:02,500
Be really, really careful of your early game.

233
00:13:02,580 --> 00:13:05,601
This is a great opportunity for skilled players to get an

234
00:13:06,042 --> 00:13:08,403
advantage that later snowballs and makes them impossible to

235
00:13:08,443 --> 00:13:09,164
stop later on.

236
00:13:09,844 --> 00:13:12,325
This goes along with the cost of, but you might make a

237
00:13:12,366 --> 00:13:14,587
mistake, because the more skilled the players are, the

238
00:13:14,647 --> 00:13:16,088
less likely they are to make a mistake.

239
00:13:16,108 --> 00:13:18,349
Their gameplay really can kind of approach perfection.

240
00:13:19,670 --> 00:13:21,451
In regular play, someone has a chance to get back in.

241
00:13:21,731 --> 00:13:23,832
But at high-skilled play, the game may be over as soon as

242
00:13:23,852 --> 00:13:25,333
someone gets a slight advantage early on.

243
00:13:26,808 --> 00:13:28,990
You see this in real-time strategy games, too, like Age

244
00:13:29,010 --> 00:13:31,932
of Empires or StarCraft, where a small economic advantage

245
00:13:32,052 --> 00:13:34,013
earlier just pays lots and lots of dividends

246
00:13:34,053 --> 00:13:34,653
by the late game.

247
00:13:38,156 --> 00:13:39,376
So I've talked most of it game design.

248
00:13:39,396 --> 00:13:41,898
But let's not forget, we're mostly talking about software

249
00:13:41,918 --> 00:13:42,999
running on hardware.

250
00:13:43,359 --> 00:13:44,360
And there are limitations.

251
00:13:45,000 --> 00:13:49,823
We recently did a study to look at play rates and win

252
00:13:49,863 --> 00:13:52,124
rates of certain league champions according to

253
00:13:52,164 --> 00:13:53,966
different ping rates.

254
00:13:54,566 --> 00:13:55,286
And we found that.

255
00:13:56,722 --> 00:13:58,382
We found that the, it's back.

256
00:13:58,922 --> 00:14:01,883
A place like Korea, which has a really good internet,

257
00:14:02,283 --> 00:14:04,704
actually allowed players to use different champions

258
00:14:04,804 --> 00:14:06,684
and have different win rates than maybe somewhere

259
00:14:06,744 --> 00:14:09,805
like the US where everyone's bouncing off

260
00:14:09,825 --> 00:14:11,065
the same servers in Chicago.

261
00:14:12,166 --> 00:14:13,886
You can mitigate this a little bit by doing things

262
00:14:13,906 --> 00:14:16,987
like making sure there's a little bit of space,

263
00:14:17,067 --> 00:14:19,207
like instead of giving players a fraction of a second

264
00:14:19,227 --> 00:14:22,748
to execute a command, you can extend that to half a second

265
00:14:22,768 --> 00:14:24,309
or something like that, which may help

266
00:14:24,749 --> 00:14:25,829
overcome latency problems.

267
00:14:29,496 --> 00:14:32,278
So this is a pretty nuanced issue I'll try to walk through.

268
00:14:33,578 --> 00:14:35,540
Tactical errors at extreme peaks of skill

269
00:14:35,580 --> 00:14:38,522
tend to be really rare, which means that who wins

270
00:14:38,562 --> 00:14:40,863
can often come down to who makes a mistake first.

271
00:14:40,943 --> 00:14:44,205
Like, two teams are playing perfectly, somebody misclicks,

272
00:14:44,245 --> 00:14:46,006
and that is the entire game ending right there.

273
00:14:46,026 --> 00:14:48,308
It can be really exciting as a viewer,

274
00:14:48,328 --> 00:14:50,289
but you're kind of left with this hollow feeling

275
00:14:50,329 --> 00:14:52,690
that it really wasn't the more skilled team that won,

276
00:14:52,991 --> 00:14:55,472
it was just the person who didn't make a mistake.

277
00:14:56,711 --> 00:15:05,638
So my lesson here is make sure that you have high-level strategies that high-level, high-skilled players can exploit, as well as tactical considerations.

278
00:15:06,038 --> 00:15:11,422
By tactics, I'm talking about things like where you're positioning your character, when you're, you know, using your different abilities.

279
00:15:12,043 --> 00:15:18,588
High-level strategy is more about, do we want to have a, you know, an early power advantage, do we want to try to sneak in their base, are we going to split lanes, things like that.

280
00:15:19,048 --> 00:15:22,150
If you have higher-level strategy, the game won't just come down to misclicking.

281
00:15:28,733 --> 00:15:30,555
So I highlighted some of the differences in trying to

282
00:15:30,595 --> 00:15:32,056
balance for both highly skilled and

283
00:15:32,116 --> 00:15:33,096
normal skilled players.

284
00:15:33,657 --> 00:15:35,338
But now we're going to make that even more complicated by

285
00:15:35,378 --> 00:15:36,959
layering on the effects of a mass audience.

286
00:15:39,560 --> 00:15:43,103
Any competitive game, any PVP game, is going to have a skill

287
00:15:43,123 --> 00:15:44,123
differential among players.

288
00:15:44,604 --> 00:15:47,145
If you're a small indie developer and you have a small

289
00:15:47,185 --> 00:15:48,826
player group, there's still going to be an enormous

290
00:15:48,846 --> 00:15:51,148
disparity in their ability to play your game.

291
00:15:52,392 --> 00:15:54,293
But League of Legends has about 100 million players.

292
00:15:54,874 --> 00:15:56,675
So that skill differential can get really large.

293
00:15:57,135 --> 00:15:59,456
Our bell curve has really long tails at both ends.

294
00:16:02,338 --> 00:16:04,799
And on top of that, we make our lives extra hard.

295
00:16:06,740 --> 00:16:08,061
He's saying the guy controlling the other five

296
00:16:08,121 --> 00:16:08,721
units almost won.

297
00:16:10,880 --> 00:16:12,841
Because in League, everyone plays by the same rules.

298
00:16:13,522 --> 00:16:16,965
This is different from, say, basketball, where the point

299
00:16:17,005 --> 00:16:19,487
lines will change depending whether you're at amateur

300
00:16:19,507 --> 00:16:21,789
college or pro play, or a game like golf where there are

301
00:16:21,809 --> 00:16:24,711
different tee boxes that different players will use.

302
00:16:27,593 --> 00:16:29,815
This is important to us because there's a virtuous

303
00:16:29,855 --> 00:16:33,258
cycle in League of people viewing the game and then

304
00:16:33,298 --> 00:16:35,060
playing the game and wanting to view the game again.

305
00:16:35,100 --> 00:16:38,222
And by viewing, this could be e-sports or streaming or any

306
00:16:39,163 --> 00:16:40,404
games players are watching on the internet.

307
00:16:42,059 --> 00:16:46,442
If you're an Asghar fan, chances are good that you're not out racing cars on the weekends.

308
00:16:46,762 --> 00:16:47,663
I don't know, maybe some of you are.

309
00:16:47,863 --> 00:16:52,407
But most people, that's kind of a sport they participate in as viewers, not necessarily as participants.

310
00:16:55,950 --> 00:17:00,014
We think this is important because in League, players look to the pros to get better.

311
00:17:00,414 --> 00:17:04,417
If I'm trying to learn jungling, I might look at, you know, what are the kind of items that Bengi picks.

312
00:17:04,457 --> 00:17:05,558
He certainly knows what he's doing.

313
00:17:06,785 --> 00:17:08,909
And there's also this aspiration of the path to pro.

314
00:17:09,870 --> 00:17:12,335
Doesn't apply to me, because I'm old and my reflexes are shot.

315
00:17:12,796 --> 00:17:14,900
But for younger players, they have this promise

316
00:17:14,920 --> 00:17:16,583
that if they just get good enough at League of Legends,

317
00:17:16,623 --> 00:17:17,705
they may make it to the big leagues

318
00:17:17,745 --> 00:17:19,388
and someone may pick them up for their e-sports team.

319
00:17:22,950 --> 00:17:25,911
As an aside though, I just want to offer a counterexample that

320
00:17:26,631 --> 00:17:29,292
while messy, multiple rulesets do have some benefits.

321
00:17:30,593 --> 00:17:32,614
We get into situations sometimes as developers where

322
00:17:32,634 --> 00:17:34,254
the problems are really over-constrained.

323
00:17:34,334 --> 00:17:38,156
Like, we can't buff this unit for the high end because it's

324
00:17:38,176 --> 00:17:40,117
already too dominant, but players at the low end can't

325
00:17:40,157 --> 00:17:40,917
necessarily use it.

326
00:17:40,937 --> 00:17:43,178
I just want to throw that out there, that it's not

327
00:17:43,198 --> 00:17:45,919
necessarily cut and dry, that one ruleset is the

328
00:17:45,939 --> 00:17:46,379
only way to go.

329
00:17:53,521 --> 00:17:56,063
So I'm going to spend the rest of the talk talking at a very

330
00:17:56,103 --> 00:17:59,985
tactical level about how Riot balances League of Legends

331
00:18:00,005 --> 00:18:00,866
with all of that in mind.

332
00:18:01,926 --> 00:18:03,387
This is the secret sauce.

333
00:18:03,847 --> 00:18:06,389
I'm going to try to be as frank as I can about what we do

334
00:18:06,429 --> 00:18:08,450
behind the scenes, because that's why we all

335
00:18:08,470 --> 00:18:09,151
come to GDC, right?

336
00:18:12,360 --> 00:18:14,481
So first, we have a philosophy.

337
00:18:14,861 --> 00:18:18,023
And I really encourage you to get your studio, your team,

338
00:18:18,063 --> 00:18:20,705
your designers aligned on your goals and values.

339
00:18:21,145 --> 00:18:23,387
Not just as a development studio, but on individual

340
00:18:23,407 --> 00:18:24,167
projects as well.

341
00:18:24,187 --> 00:18:27,429
If you have a shared philosophy, it really helps to

342
00:18:27,489 --> 00:18:28,610
arbitrate the tough calls.

343
00:18:29,010 --> 00:18:31,612
You aren't debating, are we OK with this, kind of in the

344
00:18:31,652 --> 00:18:32,212
heat of the moment.

345
00:18:32,432 --> 00:18:34,033
You already know what good looks like.

346
00:18:34,094 --> 00:18:36,315
So then when you're missing that target, you can react.

347
00:18:37,816 --> 00:18:40,518
It also provides precedence for the teams of tomorrow.

348
00:18:42,239 --> 00:18:44,500
Game development tends to be a highly mobile career.

349
00:18:44,980 --> 00:18:47,822
People will leave studios or leave teams

350
00:18:47,962 --> 00:18:49,242
or move to different teams.

351
00:18:49,702 --> 00:18:52,644
And I feel like we spend a lot of our time doing archaeology,

352
00:18:52,684 --> 00:18:55,545
like trying to understand why did the developers who

353
00:18:55,585 --> 00:18:58,066
worked on this game two years ago make this particular decision.

354
00:18:58,567 --> 00:19:01,748
So if you have goals and values that you can particularly

355
00:19:01,828 --> 00:19:04,649
publish someplace and make sure the whole company understands,

356
00:19:05,009 --> 00:19:06,670
it can help to mitigate some of that.

357
00:19:09,300 --> 00:19:11,082
So for example, these are the league design values.

358
00:19:11,402 --> 00:19:12,403
I won't go through them all here,

359
00:19:12,483 --> 00:19:14,645
but we do make sure that the changes we make

360
00:19:14,685 --> 00:19:16,107
are aligned with these values.

361
00:19:17,588 --> 00:19:20,371
The idea is that hopefully we're making the game better

362
00:19:20,411 --> 00:19:22,373
over time rather than just doing this kind of

363
00:19:22,473 --> 00:19:24,315
one step forward, two step back thing where,

364
00:19:24,615 --> 00:19:26,557
oh, we made a change, oh, that was a bad change,

365
00:19:26,577 --> 00:19:28,439
let's make another change, oh, that was another bad change.

366
00:19:28,759 --> 00:19:30,641
I mean, don't get me wrong, that still happens for sure,

367
00:19:31,081 --> 00:19:33,343
but the intent is that we're making progress.

368
00:19:34,478 --> 00:19:35,779
And it's not just design values.

369
00:19:35,919 --> 00:19:36,900
Riot has values.

370
00:19:37,240 --> 00:19:39,041
League of Legends as a product has values.

371
00:19:39,461 --> 00:19:41,083
There are values for particular, you know,

372
00:19:41,123 --> 00:19:42,043
very small project.

373
00:19:42,163 --> 00:19:43,044
It could be as narrow as,

374
00:19:43,324 --> 00:19:45,606
hey, we really need to nerf Leona's late game.

375
00:19:49,269 --> 00:19:50,850
And then, once you have that philosophy,

376
00:19:50,890 --> 00:19:52,291
make sure you actually do stick with it.

377
00:19:53,387 --> 00:19:56,988
We really like to work this way because it helps to mitigate against designers tinkering.

378
00:19:57,128 --> 00:19:59,809
And by tinkering I mean someone's driving into work and they're like,

379
00:20:00,189 --> 00:20:02,450
I had a crazy idea, let's do this and see what happens.

380
00:20:03,650 --> 00:20:06,791
That could be fun as a designer, it's really pretty painful for players.

381
00:20:07,672 --> 00:20:11,153
And it also solves the mythical, oh I had a bad game last night,

382
00:20:11,733 --> 00:20:14,234
Leona beat me so I'm going to go in and make sure the team nerfs Leona.

383
00:20:16,274 --> 00:20:17,535
Players think we work that way.

384
00:20:20,317 --> 00:20:22,239
So instead we're trying to solve specific problems

385
00:20:22,780 --> 00:20:25,223
like X is too strong in the laning phase

386
00:20:25,403 --> 00:20:28,047
rather than, hey, something popped into my head

387
00:20:28,087 --> 00:20:28,508
out of the blue.

388
00:20:29,986 --> 00:20:34,727
Now as an aside, Riot as a company really likes to work this way overall because it helps to empower our teams.

389
00:20:35,427 --> 00:20:39,528
It makes the growth of the company more scalable because instead of the same decision makers

390
00:20:39,568 --> 00:20:42,989
kind of having to swan dive into every single discussion that's going on,

391
00:20:43,369 --> 00:20:45,830
we can spend our time getting aligned on what the values are,

392
00:20:46,070 --> 00:20:49,571
and then the teams can go off and make the decisions themselves without having to like,

393
00:20:50,031 --> 00:20:53,772
reopen every discussion because we've already kind of agreed on what the high-level goals are.

394
00:20:56,682 --> 00:20:58,324
But you won't always get it right.

395
00:20:59,306 --> 00:21:00,447
One of my leads the other day said,

396
00:21:00,848 --> 00:21:03,090
even the best design that you've really thought about

397
00:21:03,130 --> 00:21:05,173
and beat up probably has about a 70% chance

398
00:21:05,213 --> 00:21:06,234
of hitting your bullseye.

399
00:21:07,135 --> 00:21:08,597
So having a risk mitigation plan

400
00:21:08,617 --> 00:21:10,259
can help to avoid panic when that happens.

401
00:21:12,049 --> 00:21:15,490
You need good KPIs and key performance indicators.

402
00:21:15,510 --> 00:21:17,731
You need to understand what you're going for here.

403
00:21:18,111 --> 00:21:19,652
If you're nerfing a champion in League,

404
00:21:19,992 --> 00:21:22,273
do we want to see her drop rate go down by 2%?

405
00:21:22,573 --> 00:21:25,415
Are we worried players aren't playing this champion

406
00:21:25,455 --> 00:21:27,576
because they're too complicated?

407
00:21:27,596 --> 00:21:29,757
They don't understand the synergies between their abilities.

408
00:21:31,117 --> 00:21:33,238
When you have good KPIs, it helps that you can agree.

409
00:21:34,312 --> 00:21:36,975
if you've missed your goals rather than debating, did we miss our goals or not.

410
00:21:37,015 --> 00:21:40,378
You immediately evaluate, okay, we missed our goals, and then you can enact the plan.

411
00:21:40,999 --> 00:21:44,102
For example, when you make a new champion, the champion designer might say,

412
00:21:44,882 --> 00:21:50,207
her weakness is supposed to be that she's not very strong in early lane,

413
00:21:50,328 --> 00:21:55,112
so if she ends up being a lane bully, nerf her Q, and that'll kind of skew her back towards the late game.

414
00:21:58,934 --> 00:22:01,916
Now we do focus on a target. We aspire to balance for all players,

415
00:22:02,656 --> 00:22:05,597
but being able to focus helps us avoid insanity.

416
00:22:06,098 --> 00:22:08,799
And this is particularly relevant because we patch the game very frequently

417
00:22:08,819 --> 00:22:10,780
and don't always have a lot of time in between patches.

418
00:22:11,240 --> 00:22:12,561
We do look at outliers at all levels,

419
00:22:12,821 --> 00:22:16,163
but I'll kind of walk you through the sweet spot for game balance.

420
00:22:18,954 --> 00:22:25,475
So if you look at how many players the changes are impacting, imagine the bottom scale here is number of players in a particular tier.

421
00:22:25,555 --> 00:22:29,936
There's a lot of bronze players, fewer silver players, only a few dozen pro players in the world.

422
00:22:32,356 --> 00:22:34,497
And this other axis is sensitivity game changes.

423
00:22:35,497 --> 00:22:42,158
So we change a champion's attack by five, a newer player isn't even going to notice that.

424
00:22:42,218 --> 00:22:43,958
They're much better off just playing ten more games.

425
00:22:43,978 --> 00:22:48,299
That will improve their win rate much more than anything that we're going to do in terms of balance.

426
00:22:50,329 --> 00:22:52,671
And then you can see the sweet spot here where these two curves intersect

427
00:22:53,111 --> 00:22:54,933
is right around high platinum, low diamond.

428
00:22:55,333 --> 00:22:59,176
That's kind of an area that we think we're impacting a lot of players still

429
00:22:59,216 --> 00:23:03,119
rather than the super rarefied air of the Challenger Master Pro tiers.

430
00:23:03,780 --> 00:23:05,501
But we still do look for outliers at all levels.

431
00:23:05,701 --> 00:23:09,725
If Garen or Master Yi is stomping Bronze, we'll take action there.

432
00:23:10,065 --> 00:23:12,647
If there's a champion that's 100% pick-ban at the Pro level,

433
00:23:12,907 --> 00:23:14,488
we'll try to take action there as well.

434
00:23:18,211 --> 00:23:18,351
Now...

435
00:23:20,035 --> 00:23:24,341
Players will assume that you should and do balance for high ELO only.

436
00:23:24,561 --> 00:23:25,943
That's the important thing to a lot of players.

437
00:23:25,963 --> 00:23:29,968
They don't necessarily understand why you're making changes that will help out less experienced players.

438
00:23:30,549 --> 00:23:34,574
But this would remove a lot of the 130 champions from those players.

439
00:23:36,070 --> 00:23:39,893
We do have to constantly reinforce the goals of balance to all within the community.

440
00:23:40,273 --> 00:23:44,617
I'll watch prominent streamers discussing the state of balance in League

441
00:23:44,637 --> 00:23:48,561
and they're always talking about, oh well now the pros are going to pick this or that,

442
00:23:49,281 --> 00:23:50,182
what is Riot thinking here?

443
00:23:51,483 --> 00:23:54,126
A lot of this stuff is publishing, and by publishing I mean

444
00:23:55,227 --> 00:23:57,389
the messaging you're sending to your communities to make sure

445
00:23:57,629 --> 00:24:01,572
they understand what your goals are and why you're making the wacky changes to the game that you're making.

446
00:24:04,366 --> 00:24:08,228
Now interestingly, pro balance itself is largely about viewers.

447
00:24:09,568 --> 00:24:12,069
We don't want to make life terrible for our pros, obviously,

448
00:24:12,449 --> 00:24:16,251
but when we make a change, it's often with the idea of our viewers

449
00:24:16,291 --> 00:24:18,292
having a fun time watching League of Legends.

450
00:24:19,392 --> 00:24:23,014
We will make changes if, for example, the game gets a little stale

451
00:24:23,054 --> 00:24:26,415
and viewers are saying, yeah, it's still fun to see the end game,

452
00:24:26,435 --> 00:24:28,936
but I skipped the first 20 minutes because it's really boring.

453
00:24:29,256 --> 00:24:30,617
That might lead us to make a change.

454
00:24:30,977 --> 00:24:33,298
In this case, balance could be fine, but we just think that, you know.

455
00:24:34,201 --> 00:24:38,423
the we're going to hurt our virtuous cycle of viewing and playing and viewing

456
00:24:38,603 --> 00:24:40,524
if people start tuning out of e-sports.

457
00:24:44,507 --> 00:24:46,568
I want to stress again, this stuff is hard.

458
00:24:47,208 --> 00:24:51,070
You can't hand this to one guy at the end of the cycle as a part-time job.

459
00:24:51,851 --> 00:24:53,672
Believe me, I was that guy in Age of Empires.

460
00:24:54,292 --> 00:24:54,772
It doesn't work.

461
00:24:55,413 --> 00:24:57,874
Certainly not with the expectations for players these days.

462
00:24:59,835 --> 00:25:01,076
It really takes a dedicated team.

463
00:25:01,916 --> 00:25:04,238
And I realize that may be challenging if you're a smaller

464
00:25:04,318 --> 00:25:07,121
indie dev, in which case I would say you're just going to

465
00:25:07,141 --> 00:25:09,543
have to leverage the feedback from your players a lot more.

466
00:25:09,864 --> 00:25:11,786
It's going to be hard for you to get tuning right.

467
00:25:12,246 --> 00:25:15,749
So if you ship your changes, listen to what players are

468
00:25:15,789 --> 00:25:17,131
saying, and then react to that.

469
00:25:17,671 --> 00:25:19,693
And I'll talk a little more about that in a second.

