00:31:06,137 --> 00:31:08,598
This is not the sign of a really well-designed champion,

585
00:31:08,999 --> 00:31:12,041
and he's the kind that is up for an update at some point.

586
00:31:12,561 --> 00:31:14,543
Now, Aurelion Sol is not awesome either.

587
00:31:14,583 --> 00:31:16,584
That's a really steep skill curve.

588
00:31:16,604 --> 00:31:20,968
We would rather the win rate not be so low at the low end.

589
00:31:26,502 --> 00:31:28,602
This is why it's so important to interpret your data.

590
00:31:29,122 --> 00:31:31,923
If you're playing against a Lee Sin, a popular jungle

591
00:31:31,943 --> 00:31:34,324
champion, the player you're playing against may very well

592
00:31:34,364 --> 00:31:36,625
have three times the number of games that you do on that

593
00:31:36,665 --> 00:31:39,326
champion, because it takes that long to get good at Lee

594
00:31:39,346 --> 00:31:41,547
Sin, so if he's showing up at all, you may be playing

595
00:31:41,587 --> 00:31:42,667
someone who really knows what they're doing.

596
00:31:43,247 --> 00:31:45,228
In this case, it's not that Lee Sin is overpowered.

597
00:31:45,248 --> 00:31:46,888
It's just you're playing against a very experienced

598
00:31:46,929 --> 00:31:47,849
player on that champion.

599
00:31:49,049 --> 00:31:51,170
This is why you have to look at things like win rate based

600
00:31:51,230 --> 00:31:54,951
on games played and win rate based on ELO to really

601
00:31:54,971 --> 00:31:55,832
understand what's going on.

602
00:31:59,343 --> 00:32:00,064
Here's another example.

603
00:32:00,745 --> 00:32:04,127
Pro champion choice has an immediate effect

604
00:32:04,187 --> 00:32:05,028
on the rest of the game.

605
00:32:05,668 --> 00:32:07,950
Once we see a pro player pick a champion,

606
00:32:07,970 --> 00:32:10,072
we know that Spike is immediately going

607
00:32:10,092 --> 00:32:11,053
to show up around the world.

608
00:32:12,330 --> 00:32:17,235
It's interesting. Part of it, I'm sure, is just, oh, the pros are really, really skilled players.

609
00:32:17,275 --> 00:32:19,838
If they know that this champion's good, they're probably good.

610
00:32:20,518 --> 00:32:23,702
I also think it's players kind of hate to be accused of not being up to date.

611
00:32:24,642 --> 00:32:28,246
Sometimes I think players would prefer to be known for poor skill

612
00:32:28,266 --> 00:32:30,228
than to be known that, you know, they were uninformed.

613
00:32:30,669 --> 00:32:32,230
Everyone hates to be wrong about things.

614
00:32:33,011 --> 00:32:38,277
So when you see particularly silver, bronze, silver, gold players pick up these pro choices,

615
00:32:38,697 --> 00:32:40,919
it's going to be an ineffective choice for them,

616
00:32:40,939 --> 00:32:44,243
because they're not going to be able to pull off the things that the pros can pull off.

617
00:32:46,565 --> 00:32:48,747
This is, uh, Froggen is known for picking Anivia.

618
00:32:51,078 --> 00:32:55,400
And speaking of Anivia, she's a great case study for why you

619
00:32:55,440 --> 00:32:57,161
need to use your judgment to make calls.

620
00:32:57,622 --> 00:33:00,063
We don't use machine learning to balance League of Legends.

621
00:33:00,123 --> 00:33:04,466
We hire people that can use their own experience as game

622
00:33:04,486 --> 00:33:07,567
designers and QA to help make these decisions.

623
00:33:08,768 --> 00:33:11,990
Anivia often turns up red flags, where her win rate can

624
00:33:12,010 --> 00:33:12,450
be as high as 55%.

625
00:33:13,851 --> 00:33:16,393
Yet we think if we nerfed her, players would be like, why did

626
00:33:16,413 --> 00:33:17,013
you nerf Anivia?

627
00:33:17,033 --> 00:33:17,753
She's not a problem.

628
00:33:18,945 --> 00:33:21,386
And when we reflect on that, we agree with them.

629
00:33:21,446 --> 00:33:24,807
Like, she has reasonable strategic counterplay,

630
00:33:24,827 --> 00:33:27,148
meaning that you can counterpick her in champion select.

631
00:33:27,648 --> 00:33:30,089
And she has reasonable tactical counterplay,

632
00:33:30,109 --> 00:33:32,170
meaning that when you're actually out on the map playing,

633
00:33:32,410 --> 00:33:34,231
there are things you can do to avoid her spells.

634
00:33:35,231 --> 00:33:36,152
So is she a balanced?

635
00:33:37,232 --> 00:33:39,153
The data says yes, but our gut says no.

636
00:33:43,014 --> 00:33:44,075
And this leads to another topic,

637
00:33:44,175 --> 00:33:46,456
which is that we don't share our data publicly.

638
00:33:47,883 --> 00:33:50,807
We didn't do this on World of Warcraft or Age of Empires either.

639
00:33:51,788 --> 00:33:57,375
The reason is we were scared that we end up dictating choices to players.

640
00:33:57,855 --> 00:34:00,979
If they see that a champion has a low win rate, they may just not play that champion.

641
00:34:01,239 --> 00:34:04,023
And really, we'd rather players just play League of Legends and have fun,

642
00:34:04,283 --> 00:34:07,166
and not obsess about becoming armchair statisticians.

643
00:34:09,908 --> 00:34:13,830
On the other hand, as a developer, or as a player, it feels really flippant when the developer says,

644
00:34:14,351 --> 00:34:17,392
well, that's not what our secret data says, and we're not going to show you our secret data.

645
00:34:17,812 --> 00:34:19,973
Makes it very hard for a player to argue against it.

646
00:34:20,654 --> 00:34:23,115
And it's possible that we could provide context. We could say, look,

647
00:34:24,075 --> 00:34:26,517
yes, this item build looks good on paper,

648
00:34:26,877 --> 00:34:30,899
but that's only with a really strong team coordination that you may not have in solo queue.

649
00:34:31,883 --> 00:34:33,724
So I just want to present this as an ongoing discussion.

650
00:34:34,324 --> 00:34:36,585
We're not changing our stance on this immediately, but we do

651
00:34:36,605 --> 00:34:37,986
discuss it a lot internally.

652
00:34:38,026 --> 00:34:40,327
And maybe it would be an interesting experiment.

653
00:34:44,429 --> 00:34:46,851
So when you detect a balance problem, how do you know what

654
00:34:46,891 --> 00:34:47,471
to change?

655
00:34:48,091 --> 00:34:49,612
In the case of League of Legends, it could be the

656
00:34:49,652 --> 00:34:52,454
champion, it could be the item, it could be the mastery.

657
00:34:52,474 --> 00:34:55,675
This is the pregame system for League of Legends, similar to

658
00:34:55,735 --> 00:34:56,436
Talents and WoW.

659
00:34:57,803 --> 00:34:59,644
Is it the strategy players are using right now?

660
00:34:59,924 --> 00:35:03,087
Is it the synergy with other champions on that team?

661
00:35:04,669 --> 00:35:07,471
There's an example of Poppy, this cute little yordle

662
00:35:07,491 --> 00:35:08,112
with the big hammer.

663
00:35:08,835 --> 00:35:12,758
We recently updated Poppy. Objectively, it was a really good rework.

664
00:35:12,878 --> 00:35:14,159
Super happy with the way that came out.

665
00:35:14,499 --> 00:35:16,220
But her win rate did spike.

666
00:35:16,841 --> 00:35:19,843
And it spiked at the same time that we changed one of our masteries.

667
00:35:20,243 --> 00:35:22,665
This is Courage of the Colossus, the green guy here.

668
00:35:23,686 --> 00:35:26,908
Courage of the Colossus gives you a shield when you crowd control a champion.

669
00:35:27,148 --> 00:35:28,650
And Poppy has a lot of crowd control.

670
00:35:28,970 --> 00:35:31,151
She's already pretty tanky. With Courage of the Colossus,

671
00:35:31,171 --> 00:35:33,513
she would get this shield and become even more tanky.

672
00:35:34,073 --> 00:35:36,794
It felt overpowered. We knew we needed to do something.

673
00:35:37,034 --> 00:35:40,915
And we debated a lot. Was Poppy the problem or was Courage of Colossus the problem?

674
00:35:41,596 --> 00:35:43,236
We definitely needed to nerf Courage of Colossus.

675
00:35:43,496 --> 00:35:45,357
The question was, did we also need to nerf Poppy?

676
00:35:46,257 --> 00:35:48,318
We went back and looked at the data in this case, and we saw that

677
00:35:48,558 --> 00:35:52,059
her win rate had started to spike even before the Courage of Colossus changed.

678
00:35:52,379 --> 00:35:53,919
So in this case, we did change both.

679
00:35:53,959 --> 00:35:56,920
We nerfed both the Mastery and the Champion at the same time.

680
00:35:56,940 --> 00:36:00,181
And if we hadn't done that, we would have had to, like, go in the next patch,

681
00:36:00,461 --> 00:36:01,762
and she still wouldn't have been fixed.

682
00:36:06,096 --> 00:36:08,317
I'm a big advocate of playtesting your own game.

683
00:36:10,057 --> 00:36:12,378
Having a playtest team, having a lot of data from players,

684
00:36:12,438 --> 00:36:14,238
is no excuse not to play the game yourself.

685
00:36:15,159 --> 00:36:16,679
If you don't, you'll miss stuff.

686
00:36:16,719 --> 00:36:18,720
You won't really understand the player experience.

687
00:36:18,800 --> 00:36:20,860
Numbers just can't tell you the entire story.

688
00:36:20,880 --> 00:36:22,241
And sometimes it's going to be really obvious.

689
00:36:22,261 --> 00:36:24,862
You're like, oh, I understand the win rate of this champion.

690
00:36:24,902 --> 00:36:27,062
It's because nobody can tell what's going on with their

691
00:36:27,082 --> 00:36:27,783
spell visuals.

692
00:36:27,823 --> 00:36:29,563
They don't know if they're standing in the fire or not.

693
00:36:31,624 --> 00:36:33,784
On the other hand, I want to caution you not to go too far

694
00:36:33,824 --> 00:36:34,565
here in the other direction.

695
00:36:35,310 --> 00:36:38,611
it can be really easy to take your experience as a player

696
00:36:38,711 --> 00:36:40,192
and assume that applies to all players.

697
00:36:40,652 --> 00:36:41,893
And I definitely see this happen

698
00:36:42,233 --> 00:36:44,434
when as a development team matures,

699
00:36:44,494 --> 00:36:45,614
meaning we're all getting older,

700
00:36:46,015 --> 00:36:48,356
it's easy for us to forget just how many games

701
00:36:48,396 --> 00:36:50,777
and how engaged some players can be with our games.

702
00:36:51,237 --> 00:36:53,778
So don't play one game and make a lot of balanced decisions

703
00:36:53,818 --> 00:36:54,719
based on that one game.

704
00:36:55,659 --> 00:36:57,680
This is in fact how we used to balance Age of Empires.

705
00:36:57,700 --> 00:36:59,761
We would go play a game, make tuning changes,

706
00:36:59,801 --> 00:37:01,362
go play another game, make tuning changes.

707
00:37:02,362 --> 00:37:03,843
Just doesn't fly, I think, anymore.

708
00:37:05,037 --> 00:37:06,338
I try to play League every day.

709
00:37:06,779 --> 00:37:07,659
I don't always succeed.

710
00:37:07,679 --> 00:37:10,122
I've been at GDC, not playing a lot of League right now.

711
00:37:10,482 --> 00:37:12,444
But it does help to stay in touch with what players are

712
00:37:12,464 --> 00:37:12,984
talking about.

713
00:37:16,387 --> 00:37:17,508
This is the best slide in the deck.

714
00:37:17,548 --> 00:37:18,329
I'll just give you a second here.

715
00:37:22,932 --> 00:37:25,274
I think the best thing is that he's just kind of, assuming

716
00:37:25,294 --> 00:37:26,235
it's a he, he's just kind of commenting.

717
00:37:26,255 --> 00:37:27,837
He's like, oh, I just noticed this.

718
00:37:27,917 --> 00:37:28,557
Kind of surprised me.

719
00:37:28,938 --> 00:37:29,598
No judgment call there.

720
00:37:32,077 --> 00:37:37,082
You do need to listen to players. We listen to our own forums, Reddit, Twitter,

721
00:37:38,123 --> 00:37:41,446
rioters who tell us they noticed something wrong, pros, streamers.

722
00:37:41,946 --> 00:37:44,629
I could give you an entire talk on leveraging player feedback.

723
00:37:45,450 --> 00:37:48,593
This doesn't mean always do immediately what the players are asking for.

724
00:37:49,033 --> 00:37:50,554
You'll often be really sad if you do that.

725
00:37:50,875 --> 00:37:52,857
But, you know, ignore them at your peril.

726
00:37:52,897 --> 00:37:55,519
They're giving you feedback. They want to see the game improved.

727
00:37:57,063 --> 00:38:00,264
You do need a good solution for other regions, other languages.

728
00:38:00,584 --> 00:38:03,245
And again, smaller studios may struggle more with this.

729
00:38:03,906 --> 00:38:06,647
Riot is fortunate enough that we have regional offices in

730
00:38:06,707 --> 00:38:08,428
all the countries where League is played.

731
00:38:08,868 --> 00:38:11,609
And we rely a lot on those teams to tell us, hey, did you

732
00:38:11,649 --> 00:38:14,750
know that players in Vietnam are talking about this problem

733
00:38:14,770 --> 00:38:16,771
in the game that may not have filtered out

734
00:38:16,791 --> 00:38:17,691
to other regions yet?

735
00:38:17,912 --> 00:38:20,653
That helps us to kind of pay attention to what Vietnamese

736
00:38:20,693 --> 00:38:22,914
players are saying, because I certainly

737
00:38:22,954 --> 00:38:23,714
can't speak Vietnamese.

738
00:38:27,202 --> 00:38:31,044
Like many companies, we also use beta tests for the changes we're going to put out.

739
00:38:32,405 --> 00:38:36,448
Betas are really good for bugs, and they're really good for impressions.

740
00:38:36,529 --> 00:38:39,070
So a player may say, wow, this is complicated,

741
00:38:39,291 --> 00:38:41,552
or I'm not exactly sure how I'm supposed to be using that.

742
00:38:42,373 --> 00:38:44,414
In general, sweeping statement here, but in general,

743
00:38:44,434 --> 00:38:46,156
betas are not good for balance testing.

744
00:38:46,736 --> 00:38:50,939
And the reason is because players understandably don't try that hard.

745
00:38:51,754 --> 00:38:54,697
If they're going to devote 10 hours this week to your game,

746
00:38:54,917 --> 00:38:57,400
they probably want to spend time in the actual game,

747
00:38:57,680 --> 00:39:00,444
not on your beta realm, trying things out that may very well

748
00:39:00,484 --> 00:39:03,287
never get shipped at the end of the day anyway.

749
00:39:03,307 --> 00:39:06,130
So you end up with smaller populations, which means

750
00:39:06,350 --> 00:39:08,553
matchmaking is not awesome, and so forth.

751
00:39:10,275 --> 00:39:12,017
I will add that on World of Warcraft.

752
00:39:12,763 --> 00:39:16,906
Testing the PvE game, meaning dungeons and raids, worked pretty well on beta,

753
00:39:16,926 --> 00:39:22,030
and that's because the high-end raiding guilds would want to get a jumpstart on the content and practice.

754
00:39:22,050 --> 00:39:24,251
So in this case, practicing did actually work out for them.

755
00:39:24,732 --> 00:39:30,856
But the PvP balance feedback from World of Warcraft beta was about as not helpful

756
00:39:30,916 --> 00:39:34,239
as the balance feedback from League of Legends betas.

757
00:39:35,519 --> 00:39:37,843
I would also discourage you from trying things like,

758
00:39:38,083 --> 00:39:39,806
oh, well, we'll bribe players to play our beta.

759
00:39:40,647 --> 00:39:42,851
You may get a short-term spike in engagement,

760
00:39:42,931 --> 00:39:45,455
but overall, you have to be really careful

761
00:39:45,936 --> 00:39:47,619
to not motivate odd behavior

762
00:39:47,639 --> 00:39:49,161
just because you want them to play a lot of games.

763
00:39:53,112 --> 00:39:55,894
We also just ask players, we don't necessarily wait for them to come to us.

764
00:39:56,394 --> 00:39:59,775
We do player labs, we bring players into the studio, have them play a game,

765
00:39:59,795 --> 00:40:01,216
then ask them about their experience.

766
00:40:01,496 --> 00:40:04,878
We do this a lot, say, for new champions or champion updates

767
00:40:05,018 --> 00:40:07,119
or crazy changes that we'd like to make to the game.

768
00:40:08,080 --> 00:40:10,862
We have a micro-survey tool that we leverage extensively.

769
00:40:11,362 --> 00:40:12,943
Anyone who's played League of Legends very long

770
00:40:12,963 --> 00:40:14,943
has probably gotten one of these surveys after a game

771
00:40:15,064 --> 00:40:17,725
asking, hey, did you like this change?

772
00:40:17,745 --> 00:40:18,685
What do you think about that?

773
00:40:19,085 --> 00:40:21,867
It's really interesting to look at how the survey feedback

774
00:40:21,907 --> 00:40:24,648
changes over time, how it changes in different regions

775
00:40:24,888 --> 00:40:25,448
around the world.

776
00:40:26,899 --> 00:40:33,781
This last preseason we added plants to the summoner's rift map that players can interact with.

777
00:40:34,042 --> 00:40:36,502
There's somewhat of a random element to the way plants spawn,

778
00:40:37,083 --> 00:40:40,044
and when players first heard about this they freaked out,

779
00:40:40,064 --> 00:40:43,205
and they thought, oh we're adding too much RNG to League of Legends, it's going to ruin the game,

780
00:40:43,245 --> 00:40:44,505
this is, you know, sky's falling.

781
00:40:45,425 --> 00:40:48,366
And nowadays, our surveys are showing that most players are

782
00:40:48,386 --> 00:40:49,906
pretty happy with the way plants ended up.

783
00:40:50,306 --> 00:40:53,267
So I'm not saying players are dumb by any stretch.

784
00:40:53,347 --> 00:40:55,548
I'm saying that we didn't necessarily set their

785
00:40:55,588 --> 00:40:57,388
expectations for what the feature was going to be.

786
00:41:01,589 --> 00:41:03,970
So now that you have goals, data, and player feedback,

787
00:41:04,050 --> 00:41:07,050
this is the basic iteration cycle that we use.

788
00:41:07,710 --> 00:41:10,591
Make changes, gather data, gather player feedback, make

789
00:41:10,651 --> 00:41:11,231
more changes.

790
00:41:11,251 --> 00:41:12,972
You may have to go through this cycle a few times.

791
00:41:15,422 --> 00:41:16,663
Let's take Nidalee, for example.

792
00:41:17,504 --> 00:41:20,065
Nidalee is a champion that can turn into a panther, which

793
00:41:20,085 --> 00:41:20,806
makes her very fast.

794
00:41:21,146 --> 00:41:22,127
She can also throw a spear.

795
00:41:22,507 --> 00:41:22,947
So guess what?

796
00:41:23,287 --> 00:41:24,488
Nidalee is our cavalry archer.

797
00:41:25,889 --> 00:41:27,930
And just as with the cavalry archers, we have trouble

798
00:41:27,990 --> 00:41:28,531
balancing her.

799
00:41:28,611 --> 00:41:32,093
So we'll make a change, doesn't fix the problem, make

800
00:41:32,113 --> 00:41:35,295
another change, doesn't fix the problem, and so on and so

801
00:41:35,395 --> 00:41:37,877
on, spoiler, she still isn't right.

802
00:41:38,497 --> 00:41:38,918
Sad Nidalee.

803
00:41:41,550 --> 00:41:43,310
Sometimes problems can't be solved through tuning.

804
00:41:43,690 --> 00:41:45,751
I mentioned before that the live team is like our first

805
00:41:45,791 --> 00:41:46,431
responders.

806
00:41:46,471 --> 00:41:48,592
They can get to the scene of an accident, but they can't

807
00:41:48,672 --> 00:41:50,052
fix traffic patterns.

808
00:41:50,292 --> 00:41:52,893
They're not empowered to rewire the stop lights to try

809
00:41:52,913 --> 00:41:54,893
to create fewer accidents overall.

810
00:41:55,793 --> 00:41:58,274
We do need sometimes to go through and make more systemic

811
00:41:58,314 --> 00:41:58,694
changes.

812
00:41:58,794 --> 00:42:00,175
We do this a lot through champion updates.

813
00:42:00,965 --> 00:42:03,967
Ryze is kind of infamous here for a champion that we just can't get right.

814
00:42:04,528 --> 00:42:07,910
We'll make a change, we'll put him out. He still is too powerful at high ELO.

815
00:42:08,150 --> 00:42:09,831
Too weak at low ELO, we'll make another change.

816
00:42:10,191 --> 00:42:11,372
And this goes on over and over.

817
00:42:15,254 --> 00:42:17,335
As a last resort, you can basement champions.

818
00:42:17,375 --> 00:42:22,298
We hate to do this because it feels like it's violating a lot of the player trust

819
00:42:22,338 --> 00:42:24,319
about being able to play the champions they want to play.

820
00:42:24,699 --> 00:42:27,401
But it's also not fair to players to give them a champion

821
00:42:27,441 --> 00:42:29,182
that is just going to ruin the experience for everyone.

822
00:42:30,478 --> 00:42:34,441
Azir is a very, very challenging champion for us to balance.

823
00:42:34,882 --> 00:42:37,364
It probably stems from the fact that he can do so many

824
00:42:37,384 --> 00:42:37,924
different things.

825
00:42:37,964 --> 00:42:40,166
He doesn't really have weaknesses that you can

826
00:42:40,206 --> 00:42:40,586
exploit.

827
00:42:41,547 --> 00:42:44,309
If we tried to tune him, given his current set of

828
00:42:44,349 --> 00:42:48,893
abilities, his win rate may be 60% at pro and 30% at bronze,

829
00:42:48,973 --> 00:42:50,294
which I'm probably exaggerating there.

830
00:42:50,314 --> 00:42:52,576
But he's definitely a hard to balance champion.

831
00:42:52,616 --> 00:42:55,018
He probably just needs an update and needs to lose some

832
00:42:55,038 --> 00:42:55,558
of what he can do.

833
00:42:57,540 --> 00:42:59,081
So winding down here a little bit.

834
00:43:00,819 --> 00:43:03,620
I've talked a ton about balance, but I want to stress

835
00:43:03,640 --> 00:43:04,880
that balance isn't everything.

836
00:43:05,120 --> 00:43:07,601
And as a systems designer, you can definitely fall into the

837
00:43:07,641 --> 00:43:09,621
trap of looking at everything through the lens of balance.

838
00:43:12,042 --> 00:43:13,942
Champions can be balanced, meaning their win rate could

839
00:43:13,962 --> 00:43:15,643
be perfect, but still really frustrating.

840
00:43:15,943 --> 00:43:19,244
And here are three examples, Riven, LeBlanc, and Yasuo.

841
00:43:21,184 --> 00:43:23,145
Yasuo's win rate may be totally fair, and enough

842
00:43:23,185 --> 00:43:24,785
players may think he's bullshit that they stop

843
00:43:24,805 --> 00:43:26,205
playing the game, which is not.

844
00:43:26,285 --> 00:43:28,426
As a developer, you don't want to say, but he's balanced.

845
00:43:31,630 --> 00:43:34,891
Likewise, remember that players pick champions for a lot of different reasons.

846
00:43:34,991 --> 00:43:38,472
I mentioned the pro example with Froggen's Anivia earlier.

847
00:43:38,952 --> 00:43:42,373
This is Jinx. She's a very popular champion to play.

848
00:43:42,933 --> 00:43:45,514
Her abilities are cool, her thematic,

849
00:43:45,594 --> 00:43:49,175
you know, she's kind of an anarchist riot girl, really resonates with players.

850
00:43:49,495 --> 00:43:51,335
We know that Jinx is always going to be popular.

851
00:43:51,695 --> 00:43:52,876
It's not necessarily because she's...

852
00:43:53,893 --> 00:43:56,255
unbalanced, and in fact right now she's a little weak of anything.

853
00:43:56,875 --> 00:44:01,398
If you look at her play rate and conclude, oh, people are playing her too much, we should nerf her,

854
00:44:01,418 --> 00:44:02,819
you're just going to make players sad.

855
00:44:07,923 --> 00:44:09,084
Being on a balanced team is hard.

856
00:44:10,124 --> 00:44:12,026
The balanced team is going to hear a lot about how terrible they are.

857
00:44:12,906 --> 00:44:15,508
Is LoL going to suffer the same fate as WoW because of Ghostcrawler?

858
00:44:17,789 --> 00:44:18,810
Burnout is really frequent.

859
00:44:19,090 --> 00:44:21,251
You're giving this team one tool to solve every problem.

860
00:44:21,271 --> 00:44:22,152
It's like, here's a wrench.

861
00:44:22,412 --> 00:44:24,233
No matter what happens, you have a wrench to solve it.

862
00:44:25,574 --> 00:44:27,775
Players and even co-workers are going to focus a lot more

863
00:44:27,815 --> 00:44:28,915
on failure than success.

864
00:44:29,776 --> 00:44:30,716
And there's never a break.

865
00:44:30,837 --> 00:44:32,277
As I said, we patch every two weeks.

866
00:44:32,317 --> 00:44:35,079
So as soon as the team is like, OK, we've made some changes

867
00:44:35,099 --> 00:44:37,340
for patch 7.5, now let's start patch 7.6.

868
00:44:38,321 --> 00:44:39,541
There's never really an off cycle.

869
00:44:41,138 --> 00:44:44,259
Some of the solutions we use are to offer side projects for

870
00:44:44,299 --> 00:44:45,039
folks on the team.

871
00:44:45,059 --> 00:44:48,580
So not everything is can I buffer nerf 5 attack damage

872
00:44:48,601 --> 00:44:48,781
here.

873
00:44:49,881 --> 00:44:51,582
We also try to rotate folks off the team.

874
00:44:51,862 --> 00:44:52,922
That's good for their sanity.

875
00:44:53,182 --> 00:44:55,963
It also helps to add some of the knowledge they've learned

876
00:44:55,983 --> 00:44:57,664
about balance to other teams as well.

877
00:44:58,984 --> 00:45:00,765
And finally, tell them they're doing good.

878
00:45:01,145 --> 00:45:02,485
They're going to hear a lot about how much

879
00:45:02,525 --> 00:45:03,226
they're screwing up.

880
00:45:03,306 --> 00:45:06,207
So it's great to reinforce with these guys how important

881
00:45:06,227 --> 00:45:06,787
their job is.

882
00:45:06,807 --> 00:45:08,908
Because they're honestly not going to hear it often from

883
00:45:08,948 --> 00:45:10,728
players, even when they legitimately are doing well.

884
00:45:13,980 --> 00:45:16,821
So in conclusion, balance matters for longevity

885
00:45:16,841 --> 00:45:17,381
and engagement.

886
00:45:17,401 --> 00:45:20,543
I would encourage you to understand why certain factors

887
00:45:20,583 --> 00:45:21,963
affect balance at different skill levels.

888
00:45:23,344 --> 00:45:24,745
I would encourage you to have a philosophy.

889
00:45:25,345 --> 00:45:28,046
Don't just make changes based on data, but making changes

890
00:45:28,086 --> 00:45:29,387
against checking against your goals.

891
00:45:30,127 --> 00:45:32,388
And iterate, iterate, iterate, and follow through when you

892
00:45:32,408 --> 00:45:33,169
don't get something right.

893
00:45:35,610 --> 00:45:36,410
You're going to screw up a lot.

894
00:45:37,151 --> 00:45:38,933
I screw up a lot, Wright screws up a lot.

895
00:45:39,494 --> 00:45:40,375
Follow up when it does.

896
00:45:41,196 --> 00:45:43,098
Having a good relationship with your community will help.

897
00:45:43,579 --> 00:45:46,502
We work really hard on this because players will give us

898
00:45:46,522 --> 00:45:48,204
the benefit of the doubt when we do make a mistake.

899
00:45:48,224 --> 00:45:49,406
They won't doubt our intentions,

900
00:45:50,007 --> 00:45:51,328
they'll just doubt our competence a little bit.

901
00:45:53,130 --> 00:45:54,191
Good luck, and with that,

902
00:45:54,552 --> 00:45:55,653
I'd be happy to take any questions.

903
00:45:55,974 --> 00:45:56,214
Thank you.

904
00:46:05,057 --> 00:46:10,199
Hey. So when nerfing things, how do you mitigate the kind of

905
00:46:10,239 --> 00:46:14,981
feel bad effects of loss aversion? Do you actually take

906
00:46:15,001 --> 00:46:16,962
that into account in making your design decisions or is that

907
00:46:17,002 --> 00:46:19,343
mostly a PR community management thing?

908
00:46:20,136 --> 00:46:21,898
I mean, it is a community management thing,

909
00:46:21,998 --> 00:46:24,600
but we involve the people making the changes as well.

910
00:46:25,421 --> 00:46:26,902
I think that's a very real concern.

911
00:46:26,922 --> 00:46:28,363
And I think as developers, we don't always

912
00:46:28,403 --> 00:46:29,324
pay enough attention to it.

913
00:46:29,584 --> 00:46:30,765
It's really easy to focus, again,

914
00:46:30,885 --> 00:46:34,168
on let's make that 50% number show up for every champion

915
00:46:34,509 --> 00:46:36,330
and to forget how it's going to feel for players.

916
00:46:37,443 --> 00:46:40,505
One thing to avoid is the Nidalee example, where you make

917
00:46:40,545 --> 00:46:43,046
a change, you don't quite hit it right, so the next patch,

918
00:46:43,086 --> 00:46:45,087
there's another nerf, the next patch, there's another nerf.

919
00:46:45,988 --> 00:46:47,488
That starts to feel really bad for players.

920
00:46:47,588 --> 00:46:49,469
They know every time they're going to open up patch notes,

921
00:46:49,489 --> 00:46:50,169
they're going to see a nerf.

922
00:46:51,030 --> 00:46:54,832
I'd encourage you in those cases to make sure you get it

923
00:46:54,892 --> 00:46:58,113
right, if you've tried a few times, or let it ride for a

924
00:46:58,133 --> 00:46:59,314
little bit, kind of let them recover.

925
00:47:00,154 --> 00:47:01,735
We also work really hard on our patch notes

926
00:47:01,755 --> 00:47:02,735
to provide context.

927
00:47:02,795 --> 00:47:04,856
Like, look, it's not that we hate Nidalee, it's that we're

928
00:47:04,876 --> 00:47:06,377
trying to solve this particular problem.

929
00:47:07,458 --> 00:47:10,599
I also think Riot, like many studios, is a little too quick

930
00:47:10,639 --> 00:47:12,080
to nerf and a little slow to buff.

931
00:47:12,260 --> 00:47:13,761
I mean, nerfing is much easier than buffing.

932
00:47:14,081 --> 00:47:18,263
But when you offset that a little bit, it's not as

933
00:47:18,303 --> 00:47:19,443
negative experience overall.

934
00:47:20,124 --> 00:47:20,664
It's a great question.

935
00:47:22,506 --> 00:47:23,386
Hi, you mentioned...

936
00:47:24,126 --> 00:47:25,607
Sorry, I'm stealing the microphone. Thanks.

937
00:47:26,087 --> 00:47:27,528
You mentioned basementing?

938
00:47:27,948 --> 00:47:28,128
Yes.

939
00:47:28,348 --> 00:47:30,209
What does that mean? Can you explain that?

940
00:47:30,809 --> 00:47:32,530
That means you...

941
00:47:33,150 --> 00:47:35,411
Your champion is such a problem in the game

942
00:47:35,451 --> 00:47:37,912
that the only thing to do is just nerf the crap out of them

943
00:47:37,932 --> 00:47:39,033
so the players aren't going to play them.

944
00:47:40,033 --> 00:47:43,937
Players who love that champion will play them, will probably still show up in lower tiers.

945
00:47:44,358 --> 00:47:47,381
It's a really shitty thing to do, particularly for players who love that champion.

946
00:47:47,721 --> 00:47:53,067
But you also, it's hard to justify having that character in the game ruining the experience for everyone else,

947
00:47:53,127 --> 00:47:55,029
just so the players that love that champion can do it.

948
00:47:55,909 --> 00:47:58,512
Quick follow-up, how do you handle messaging around that?

949
00:47:58,552 --> 00:48:01,595
Is there a strategy there, or do you just do it quietly and hope people keep quiet?

950
00:48:02,123 --> 00:48:06,365
My general policy is to be as honest with players as you can.

951
00:48:06,385 --> 00:48:06,945
They're smart.

952
00:48:06,965 --> 00:48:07,766
They're going to figure it out.

953
00:48:07,826 --> 00:48:09,466
They're not going to buy your bullshit excuse.

954
00:48:09,546 --> 00:48:12,108
So in those cases, I would say, look, we screwed up.

955
00:48:12,148 --> 00:48:15,009
We can't make this character or unit or whatever game

956
00:48:15,029 --> 00:48:15,449
you're working on.

957
00:48:15,469 --> 00:48:16,710
We can't make this healthy right now.

958
00:48:17,030 --> 00:48:19,971
We're going to temporarily kind of park them, and we are

959
00:48:19,991 --> 00:48:20,691
going to get back to it.

960
00:48:20,711 --> 00:48:21,512
You do need to follow up.

961
00:48:21,552 --> 00:48:23,533
You just can't leave them in that state forever.

962
00:48:23,913 --> 00:48:25,854
We did that once with a champion named Olaf, and

963
00:48:25,874 --> 00:48:27,815
players still call it Olafing is the verb.

964
00:48:29,015 --> 00:48:29,215
Thanks.

965
00:48:31,135 --> 00:48:38,383
Hi, great talk. I have a question about the amount of champions you have and as the meta progresses

966
00:48:38,783 --> 00:48:40,946
Some of them will will be underrepresented

967
00:48:41,446 --> 00:48:46,772
So when you're doing updates like buffs and nerves, do you usually look at the underrepresented?

968
00:48:47,413 --> 00:48:49,836
Champions and buff them so they could be more relevant

969
00:48:50,396 --> 00:48:54,840
We look at champions who have a lower win rate and try to buff them to stay relevant,

970
00:48:55,341 --> 00:48:57,562
assuming that we can do so in a healthy way.

971
00:48:59,084 --> 00:49:01,066
Galio is a champion we're working on right now.

972
00:49:01,486 --> 00:49:03,368
His abilities just aren't that exciting.

973
00:49:03,408 --> 00:49:04,589
Volibear is another example.

974
00:49:04,629 --> 00:49:06,971
So we'd be hesitant to buff them excessively.

975
00:49:07,511 --> 00:49:10,013
We don't buff champions just based on low play rate.

976
00:49:10,454 --> 00:49:13,336
We have champions like Urgot.

977
00:49:13,717 --> 00:49:15,078
He's a creepy dude.

978
00:49:15,839 --> 00:49:18,100
We don't necessarily want to see Urgot as popular as Jinx.

979
00:49:18,160 --> 00:49:20,422
That's part of why players like to play him, is he's a little

980
00:49:20,462 --> 00:49:20,782
weird.

981
00:49:20,862 --> 00:49:23,224
So in that case, we're fine, as long as there are players out

982
00:49:23,244 --> 00:49:24,204
there that love that champion.

983
00:49:24,224 --> 00:49:25,145
All right.

984
00:49:25,405 --> 00:49:25,625
Thank you.

985
00:49:27,487 --> 00:49:31,208
You talked a lot about how higher play rate on champions.

986
00:49:31,228 --> 00:49:33,489
So for example, if a player plays a champion a lot,

987
00:49:33,729 --> 00:49:35,789
their skill will increase with that champion.

988
00:49:36,549 --> 00:49:38,770
So if you take this and you add it to the fact

989
00:49:38,790 --> 00:49:42,411
that there's 130 champions and only six bands

990
00:49:42,491 --> 00:49:46,052
for ranked online, it seems as if you're

991
00:49:46,552 --> 00:49:47,752
encouraging one tricks.

992
00:49:47,972 --> 00:49:51,393
Is that intentional or is that kind of a side effect of?

993
00:49:53,094 --> 00:49:56,577
It's a side effect and I hate it and I think it's one of the biggest design challenges

994
00:49:56,617 --> 00:49:58,198
you have to fix in League of Legends overall.

995
00:49:58,839 --> 00:50:03,402
If you ask a skilled player, how do I get better at ranked, they'll tell you, be a one

996
00:50:03,422 --> 00:50:03,902
trick pony.

997
00:50:04,223 --> 00:50:07,325
Find one champion, play the hell out of that champion, know everything there is to know

998
00:50:07,385 --> 00:50:08,146
about that champion.

999
00:50:09,426 --> 00:50:12,989
And that is effective, and you will increase your win rate

1000
00:50:13,029 --> 00:50:14,650
and probably the tier you play in.

1001
00:50:15,510 --> 00:50:18,352
Unfortunately, it leaves a huge variety of the game

1002
00:50:19,293 --> 00:50:20,053
unavailable to you.

1003
00:50:20,313 --> 00:50:21,834
We try to offer all these champions

1004
00:50:21,854 --> 00:50:22,795
for a lot of diversity.

1005
00:50:23,055 --> 00:50:25,717
In fact, we know that people who play more champions tend

1006
00:50:25,757 --> 00:50:27,098
to stick with the game longer and say that

1007
00:50:27,118 --> 00:50:27,918
they're having more fun.

1008
00:50:28,279 --> 00:50:30,740
You can imagine burnout is probably higher when you've

1009
00:50:30,760 --> 00:50:31,301
played 300 games with Vi.

1010
00:50:33,402 --> 00:50:36,087
You can imagine that when Vi gets nerfed, you may just

1011
00:50:36,127 --> 00:50:37,429
churn out of the game rather than switching

1012
00:50:37,449 --> 00:50:38,191
to another champion.

1013
00:50:38,531 --> 00:50:40,395
So I don't have good solutions to that.

1014
00:50:40,535 --> 00:50:41,717
It keeps me up at night for sure.

1015
00:50:41,737 --> 00:50:42,819
Thank you.

1016
00:50:44,311 --> 00:50:58,574
So I had a question revolving around champion tiering, which is just this sort of construct that other players have constructed to say these champions are tier 1, these champions are tier 2, which basically represents like pick these first and these guys are niche and these guys are useless.

1017
00:50:59,674 --> 00:51:06,416
Do you embrace champion tiering and say we're building this guy to be tier 1 and this other guy is some really niche...

1018
00:51:07,136 --> 00:51:10,118
counter and that's okay and he's not going to be high pick.

1019
00:51:10,639 --> 00:51:14,642
I guess it revolves around are you striving for even pick rates or do you sort of embrace

1020
00:51:15,322 --> 00:51:19,305
the tiers? No we don't strive for even pick rates.

1021
00:51:19,645 --> 00:51:22,427
There are champions that are really good at particular things.

1022
00:51:23,228 --> 00:51:26,570
Shen is a good split pusher. If you don't enjoy split pushing or

1023
00:51:26,970 --> 00:51:29,732
that strategy currently isn't super powerful in the game

1024
00:51:30,353 --> 00:51:31,273
he may not be a great pick.

1025
00:51:32,715 --> 00:51:34,837
We want that a player who loves a champion to have

1026
00:51:34,877 --> 00:51:35,998
opportunities to play them.

1027
00:51:36,519 --> 00:51:39,401
It feels terrible if you love this champion, you've invested

1028
00:51:39,421 --> 00:51:41,323
a lot in them, maybe you've spent a lot of money on skins

1029
00:51:41,343 --> 00:51:43,605
for this champion, and now you feel like you just can't play

1030
00:51:43,625 --> 00:51:45,067
them, that's a really terrible experience.

1031
00:51:46,808 --> 00:51:48,850
And then I had a request from another gentleman to go back

1032
00:51:48,890 --> 00:51:49,951
to the conclusions page.

1033
00:51:50,612 --> 00:51:51,733
I think he wanted to take some notes.

1034
00:51:53,535 --> 00:51:53,795
There we go.

1035
00:51:55,349 --> 00:51:55,829
Hey, how's it going?

1036
00:51:56,109 --> 00:51:56,610
Hey.

1037
00:51:56,650 --> 00:51:58,792
You talked about not only having a philosophy,

1038
00:51:58,832 --> 00:51:59,853
but following it.

1039
00:52:00,054 --> 00:52:02,296
I'm wondering if you can give some example actions

1040
00:52:02,336 --> 00:52:04,598
of what you've done to incorporate your philosophy

1041
00:52:04,618 --> 00:52:06,580
into your team, so it's actually part of the culture.

1042
00:52:09,964 --> 00:52:11,686
We talk a lot about it, for starters.

1043
00:52:11,726 --> 00:52:14,709
I make sure that we reinforce with the team.

1044
00:52:16,809 --> 00:52:18,670
We give teams a lot of autonomy at Riot.

1045
00:52:19,110 --> 00:52:22,112
And so then when someone makes a mistake, we'll retro it.

1046
00:52:22,132 --> 00:52:22,872
We'll talk about it.

1047
00:52:22,912 --> 00:52:25,853
Like, did we make this change to this champion

1048
00:52:25,893 --> 00:52:27,454
because we really thought players would embrace it?

1049
00:52:27,494 --> 00:52:28,835
Or did we make this change to the champion

1050
00:52:28,855 --> 00:52:30,936
because you thought it was fun as a designer?

1051
00:52:31,096 --> 00:52:33,117
I mean, sometimes good things come out of that.

1052
00:52:33,157 --> 00:52:35,238
But again, I feel like it's not super fair to players

1053
00:52:35,498 --> 00:52:38,259
to just use them as our playground like that.

1054
00:52:40,000 --> 00:52:41,641
We retro things, we talk about what went wrong,

1055
00:52:41,681 --> 00:52:43,923
we try not to beat up our teams too much for mistakes,

1056
00:52:44,043 --> 00:52:46,124
unless there's kind of a repeated pattern

1057
00:52:46,384 --> 00:52:48,326
of making the same mistakes and not learning from that.

1058
00:52:48,882 --> 00:52:53,626
So is it really on the onus of the leadership team to make sure they're hitting those talking points then?

1059
00:52:53,866 --> 00:53:00,472
Yeah, absolutely. I describe my job a lot. I do not balance League of Legends. You wouldn't want me to. It would be a travesty.

1060
00:53:01,853 --> 00:53:06,296
What I do is I talk more about creating an ecosystem in which good design decisions get made.

1061
00:53:06,677 --> 00:53:09,759
So I try to make sure people are thinking about things in frameworks.

1062
00:53:09,779 --> 00:53:16,284
And then, frankly, we just hire good people and smart designers and try to make sure they're aligned with our high-level values

1063
00:53:16,384 --> 00:53:18,106
and then turn them loose and get out of their way.

1064
00:53:18,770 --> 00:53:18,995
Thank you.

1065
00:53:21,222 --> 00:53:23,964
First, thank you for your inspiring presentation.

1066
00:53:24,945 --> 00:53:28,988
I'd like to ask about the balancing of champions

1067
00:53:29,348 --> 00:53:30,529
in several stages.

1068
00:53:31,069 --> 00:53:33,031
Like, for example, you nerf one of them,

1069
00:53:33,531 --> 00:53:34,872
you see that it's not enough,

1070
00:53:35,332 --> 00:53:37,154
or it's over the edge,

1071
00:53:37,174 --> 00:53:39,355
and the next iteration you buff it a lot.

1072
00:53:39,896 --> 00:53:42,498
So which way do you prefer?

1073
00:53:43,558 --> 00:53:45,280
Do you take one champion,

1074
00:53:46,000 --> 00:53:47,081
apply some changes,

1075
00:53:47,241 --> 00:53:49,903
and then let it sit for a while?

1076
00:53:50,797 --> 00:53:53,579
and come to it later, a lot later probably,

1077
00:53:53,599 --> 00:54:00,383
or do you try to iterate in successful patches

1078
00:54:00,644 --> 00:54:01,384
until he's perfect?

1079
00:54:02,185 --> 00:54:03,666
It really depends on the situation.

1080
00:54:03,806 --> 00:54:05,527
As I mentioned a little bit ago,

1081
00:54:06,167 --> 00:54:07,368
I caution you not to like,

1082
00:54:08,209 --> 00:54:10,070
nerf the same character over and over again.

1083
00:54:10,090 --> 00:54:11,591
I mean this happened on World of Warcraft as well,

1084
00:54:11,611 --> 00:54:13,152
where we couldn't quite solve a problem,

1085
00:54:13,192 --> 00:54:15,134
and so patch after patch there's another,

1086
00:54:15,314 --> 00:54:17,175
you know, feral druid nerf or whatever.

1087
00:54:19,076 --> 00:54:20,919
Nerfing tends to be easier than buffing, particularly when

1088
00:54:20,939 --> 00:54:23,663
you're looking at a situation where we have 10 champions that

1089
00:54:23,683 --> 00:54:24,725
are OK and one outlier.

1090
00:54:24,745 --> 00:54:26,508
And players are always like, well, why don't you buff the

1091
00:54:26,528 --> 00:54:29,152
other nine to be equal to that win rate?

1092
00:54:29,713 --> 00:54:31,215
That's just a lot harder to do.

1093
00:54:33,230 --> 00:54:36,033
If you keep missing the mark, you need to step back

1094
00:54:36,093 --> 00:54:37,975
and understand why are you missing the mark.

1095
00:54:38,055 --> 00:54:39,657
Is your data collection flawed?

1096
00:54:39,917 --> 00:54:41,499
Are you just changing the wrong thing?

1097
00:54:41,839 --> 00:54:43,901
Are players adjusting as quickly as you can?

1098
00:54:44,222 --> 00:54:47,265
Sometimes it does help just to step back and see what happens.

1099
00:54:47,665 --> 00:54:49,167
It can take the community a while

1100
00:54:49,247 --> 00:54:51,950
to develop a counter strategy to a dominant strategy.

1101
00:54:52,350 --> 00:54:56,812
We do try to, you know, we describe our relationship to League's balance as curation.

1102
00:54:56,852 --> 00:55:00,413
Like Riot doesn't kind of let it out in the wild and then whatever happens, happens.

1103
00:55:00,453 --> 00:55:03,355
We do try to step in when players are experiencing too much pain.

1104
00:55:04,395 --> 00:55:04,715
Thank you.

1105
00:55:06,476 --> 00:55:09,797
Hi. I wanted to get some more of your thoughts on the...

1106
00:55:10,781 --> 00:55:13,282
the relationship between viewership and changes.

1107
00:55:14,243 --> 00:55:16,784
Like one contrast to traditional sports like soccer,

1108
00:55:17,224 --> 00:55:18,665
there's no balance changes to the game.

1109
00:55:18,725 --> 00:55:19,926
It hardly ever evolves.

1110
00:55:21,406 --> 00:55:22,427
But on the eSports side,

1111
00:55:22,927 --> 00:55:24,588
every time you're making a change, balancing,

1112
00:55:24,988 --> 00:55:26,169
I know you mentioned that you do keep

1113
00:55:26,289 --> 00:55:27,129
viewership into account,

1114
00:55:27,770 --> 00:55:29,310
but how much relationship is there?

1115
00:55:31,371 --> 00:55:33,512
Is there a risk of them getting out of touch with the game

1116
00:55:33,833 --> 00:55:35,433
and then not understanding what they're watching?

1117
00:55:37,376 --> 00:55:41,159
Yeah, absolutely. We do, you know, we have to take that into consideration when we make changes.

1118
00:55:41,219 --> 00:55:44,681
We know that the changes we make are going to affect the pros.

1119
00:55:44,701 --> 00:55:47,483
One of the things we try to do is, you know, keep them in the loop.

1120
00:55:47,563 --> 00:55:48,664
Like, as part of the discussion, like,

1121
00:55:48,904 --> 00:55:51,445
hey guys, just want to let you know, we're thinking about making this change,

1122
00:55:51,545 --> 00:55:52,526
you know, what's your reaction?

1123
00:55:52,886 --> 00:55:55,808
We don't let them balance the game for us, but we do want to get their feedback,

1124
00:55:55,848 --> 00:55:57,309
because they're very in touch with that.

1125
00:55:57,990 --> 00:56:01,651
We also know that making systemic changes, like for example,

1126
00:56:01,931 --> 00:56:04,271
not that long ago we changed the dragon in League of Legends

1127
00:56:04,291 --> 00:56:06,792
to actually be five different dragons that kind of spawn at random.

1128
00:56:07,332 --> 00:56:11,773
We rely a lot on our casters and analysts to help explain this to viewers.

1129
00:56:11,813 --> 00:56:14,773
We have Riot is Blessed's very exceptional talent there,

1130
00:56:15,073 --> 00:56:18,094
and they can kind of help bring players along on that journey

1131
00:56:18,114 --> 00:56:19,134
to understand what's going on.

1132
00:56:19,534 --> 00:56:20,775
It's a very complicated game.

1133
00:56:21,915 --> 00:56:22,175
Thank you.

1134
00:56:24,066 --> 00:56:28,888
Hello, I wanted to ask about if an AI controlled champion

1135
00:56:28,968 --> 00:56:31,229
being good in high ELO and low ELO,

1136
00:56:31,309 --> 00:56:32,610
like how would you balance that out

1137
00:56:32,670 --> 00:56:34,191
if it's very popular on the low ELO?

1138
00:56:35,591 --> 00:56:36,431
It's challenging.

1139
00:56:37,212 --> 00:56:40,613
We have a champion named Ivern, who's like a happy tree guy,

1140
00:56:41,053 --> 00:56:44,574
who has an AI, a boulder creature named Daisy.

1141
00:56:45,014 --> 00:56:48,175
And he's been pretty popular, pretty high win rate recently,

1142
00:56:48,215 --> 00:56:49,115
despite the AI.

1143
00:56:49,335 --> 00:56:51,896
I think that's because not that much of his power budget

1144
00:56:51,936 --> 00:56:53,116
is tied up in the AI.

1145
00:56:53,156 --> 00:56:54,977
He can do a lot of cool things in addition to that.

1146
00:56:55,317 --> 00:56:58,658
So if you want to have a champion that uses a lot,

1147
00:56:58,778 --> 00:57:01,179
a character in your game that uses a lot of turrets or AI,

1148
00:57:01,519 --> 00:57:03,739
I would say just make sure that the power budget is

1149
00:57:03,979 --> 00:57:04,780
pretty small there.

1150
00:57:05,218 --> 00:57:05,398
OK.

1151
00:57:06,018 --> 00:57:07,639
I think we have about three minutes left.

1152
00:57:07,679 --> 00:57:09,761
If we run out of time, I'm going to go over

1153
00:57:09,801 --> 00:57:12,042
to the wrap-up room, which is right by the escalators

1154
00:57:12,062 --> 00:57:12,462
to the left.

1155
00:57:14,076 --> 00:57:19,100
Different countries have different preferences in aesthetic choices and champions they might choose.

1156
00:57:19,700 --> 00:57:25,564
How does that play into how you decide, because different countries have different playstyle choices as well?

1157
00:57:25,765 --> 00:57:26,425
Yeah, absolutely.

1158
00:57:26,925 --> 00:57:29,487
Overall we've found that players are players, and

1159
00:57:29,968 --> 00:57:34,131
if a champion is cool in one region, it tends to be popular in other regions as well.

1160
00:57:34,771 --> 00:57:36,532
There are definitely regional differences.

1161
00:57:37,713 --> 00:57:41,616
Chinese players love big guys with swords. We probably couldn't make enough big guys with swords.

1162
00:57:42,537 --> 00:57:46,899
A character like Jinx, who's like this anarchist rebel, that archetype just doesn't resonate as

1163
00:57:46,999 --> 00:57:51,741
much historically in their culture as it does, say, in the West. And that's fine. We know

1164
00:57:51,781 --> 00:57:55,383
there's going to be regional differences. Some places are going to embrace a champion more than

1165
00:57:55,443 --> 00:58:00,046
others. We try to offer diversity there. We do have 130, so hopefully there will be something

1166
00:58:00,086 --> 00:58:00,486
for everyone.

1167
00:58:00,757 --> 00:58:03,498
But do you actually make any choices saying,

1168
00:58:03,518 --> 00:58:06,521
this country may like this aesthetic,

1169
00:58:06,961 --> 00:58:10,143
and we want them to maybe try different play styles.

1170
00:58:10,203 --> 00:58:12,765
So we're going to actually give them this aesthetic

1171
00:58:12,805 --> 00:58:14,146
with a varying play style.

1172
00:58:14,866 --> 00:58:17,148
One strategy we use that can help there

1173
00:58:17,188 --> 00:58:19,830
are the champion skins, which change the look and sometimes

1174
00:58:19,870 --> 00:58:21,170
the voice of a champion quite a bit.

1175
00:58:21,551 --> 00:58:25,533
So we can introduce a champion or a line of skins

1176
00:58:25,594 --> 00:58:25,794
that

1177
00:58:26,534 --> 00:58:29,618
you know, has to do with a holiday or historical event in some country,

1178
00:58:29,658 --> 00:58:31,520
knowing that they may not have widespread appeal,

1179
00:58:31,540 --> 00:58:32,581
but those players are going to love it.

1180
00:58:33,442 --> 00:58:33,623
Cheers.

1181
00:58:35,545 --> 00:58:40,451
How do you feel about players and fan sites gathering and sharing data

1182
00:58:40,551 --> 00:58:43,414
in order to help each other to play the game?

1183
00:58:43,434 --> 00:58:44,776
That's a really good question.

1184
00:58:46,238 --> 00:58:48,059
I mean, overall, I don't begrudge them from doing that.

1185
00:58:48,099 --> 00:58:49,479
It totally makes sense why players

1186
00:58:49,579 --> 00:58:50,940
want that information, particularly given

1187
00:58:50,960 --> 00:58:51,800
that we don't provide it.

1188
00:58:52,321 --> 00:58:54,742
The challenge is that sometimes the data is wrong.

1189
00:58:55,362 --> 00:58:57,943
And in those cases, as developers,

1190
00:58:57,983 --> 00:59:00,204
we don't have the bandwidth to go debug it and explain

1191
00:59:00,224 --> 00:59:01,265
